    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-04-11T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-04-11T10:00:00-05:00" n="316"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d316">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">784A.5/4–1151: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Israel</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DAC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d316fn1">Repeated to Amman and Jerusalem.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tel Aviv</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-04-11T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >April 11, 1951—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>645. Having heard that this govt was planning an official celebration in
                    Jerusalem on May 11, I took occasion recently to review briefly the policy set
                    forth in <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 340, February 14<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d316fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_580">p. 580</ref>.</note> when
                    on a routine visit to the <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> to make
                    arrangements for the entertainment of official visitors. This was done to
                    forestall if possible receiving an official invitation to celebration or at
                    least prepare a basis for non-attendance shld one nevertheless be recd.</p>
                <p>I have now been asked informally whether I wld consider it consistent with our
                    policy to attend such a celebration in Jerusalem and have expressed the view
                    that it wld not be consistent with such policy. I thanked the <gloss
                        target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> spokesman for taking matter up in this
                    way and said I hoped no invitation wld be reed in circumstances. I understand my
                    Brit, French and Belgian colleagues agree this view.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DAC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
